TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS DOCUMENT

The Seraph Stack v1.0

Intelligent Systems Architecture Framework

Document ID: SS-TS-1.0
Classification: Confidential - Proprietary
Last Updated: 2024-Q3
Architecture Version: Seraph-1.0 (Cohort Release)

---

1. ARCHITECTURAL OVERVIEW & PRINCIPLES

1.1 Core Philosophy

The Seraph Stack implements a Triune Intelligence Pattern where three autonomous but interdependent cognitive layers operate in continuous feedback loops, creating emergent system intelligence beyond individual component capabilities.

1.2 Foundational Principles

· Autonomous Integrity: Security as intrinsic property, not external layer
· Semantic Coherence: Data understood by meaning, not just structure
· Recursive Optimization: Systems continuously self-tune toward homeostasis
· Ethical By Design: Governance embedded in operational logic

1.3 System Topology

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                 COORDINATION LAYER                   │
│         Seraph-Orchestrator (Meta-Controller)        │
└──────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────┘
                           │
    ┌──────────────────────┼──────────────────────┐
    │                      │                      │
┌───▼──────┐         ┌────▼─────┐         ┌──────▼───┐
│  SENTINEL │         │   NEXUS  │         │  RESTOR  │
│  Pillar   │◄───────┤  Pillar  ├────────►│  Pillar  │
└───┬──────┘         └────┬─────┘         └──────┬───┘
    │                      │                      │
    └──────────────────────┼──────────────────────┘
                           │
┌──────────────────────────▼──────────────────────────┐
│            UNIFIED DATA FABRIC LAYER                │
│  Semantic Graph + Event Stream + Immutable Ledger   │
└──────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────┘
                           │
┌──────────────────────────▼──────────────────────────┐
│            INFRASTRUCTURE ABSTRACTION               │
│         (Cloud, Edge, On-Prem, Hybrid)              │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

---

2. PILLAR 1: SERAPH-SENTINEL TECHNICAL SPECIFICATION

2.1 Core Components

2.1.1 Integrity Validator Engine

· Technology: Zero-Knowledge Proof circuits + TEE (Trusted Execution Environment)
· Processing: 10,000 validations/sec per node
· Latency: <50ms for integrity proofs
· Consensus: Practical Byzantine Fault Tolerance (pBFT) for validation consensus

2.1.2 Adaptive Threat Intelligence Core

```
Architecture:
├── Behavioral Baseline Engine (7-day learning period)
├── Anomaly Detection: Isolation Forest + LSTM hybrid
├── Threat Prediction: Graph Neural Networks (GNN)
├── Response Generator: Reinforcement Learning agent
└── Policy Enforcer: Rego-based (Open Policy Agent)

Metrics:
- False Positive Rate: <0.1%
- Threat Detection Time: <200ms from IOC emergence
- Automated Response Rate: 85% of Tier 1-3 threats
```

2.1.3 Ethical Boundary Controller

· Framework: Constitutional AI constraints with runtime monitoring
· Audit Trail: Immutable, cryptographically-sealed event log
· Compliance Mapping: Automated regulation → code translation (GDPR, HIPAA, etc.)

2.2 Key Interfaces

API Gateway: Sentinel-API v1

```yaml
endpoints:
  /v1/integrity/validate:
    method: POST
    input: {data: any, context: object, policy_id: string}
    output: {valid: bool, proof: string, violations: array}
    
  /v1/threat/assess:
    method: WebSocket (real-time stream)
    protocols: gRPC, WebSocket
    sla: 99.99% uptime, <100ms p95 latency
    
  /v1/policy/deploy:
    method: PUT
    input: Rego policy + natural language description
    output: Compiled WASM policy with version hash
```

Data Schema: Sentinel Events

```protobuf
message SentinelEvent {
  string event_id = 1;
  google.protobuf.Timestamp timestamp = 2;
  string pillar_id = 3;  // "sentinel"
  
  oneof event_type {
    IntegrityViolation integrity = 4;
    ThreatDetected threat = 5;
    PolicyViolation policy = 6;
    SystemCompromise compromise = 7;
  }
  
  message IntegrityViolation {
    string resource_id = 1;
    string expected_hash = 2;
    string actual_hash = 3;
    Severity severity = 4;
  }
  
  enum Severity {
    LOW = 0;
    MEDIUM = 1;
    HIGH = 2;
    CRITICAL = 3;
  }
}
```

2.3 Performance Specifications

· Throughput: 1M events/second per cluster node
· Latency: P95 < 150ms for validation responses
· Recovery: Automated failover within 2 seconds
· Scalability: Linear scaling to 1000+ nodes

---

3. PILLAR 2: SERAPH-NEXUS TECHNICAL SPECIFICATION

3.1 Core Components

3.1.1 Unified Semantic Interpreter

```
Architecture:
├── Schema Registry: Protobuf/Avro/JSON Schema with versioning
├── Ontology Engine: RDF/OWL with domain-specific extensions
├── Context Manager: Maintains session/transaction context
└── Quality Scorer: Data quality metrics (completeness, accuracy, timeliness)

Capabilities:
- Real-time schema evolution without downtime
- Cross-format translation: 50+ formats supported
- Context preservation across 1000+ hops
```

3.1.2 Knowledge Graph Engine

· Storage: Native graph database (Neo4j/TigerGraph) + vector store
· Scale: 10B+ entities, 100B+ relationships
· Query Language: Cypher + GQL + SPARQL unification layer
· Inference: OWL 2 RL reasoner with custom rulesets

3.1.3 Narrative Synthesis Engine

· Model: Fine-tuned LLM (70B parameters) with RAG architecture
· Input: Structured data + unstructured text + temporal sequences
· Output: Natural language reports, executive summaries, alerts
· Customization: Domain-specific fine-tuning (finance, healthcare, etc.)

3.2 Key Interfaces

API Gateway: Nexus-API v1

```yaml
endpoints:
  /v1/translate:
    method: POST
    input: {data: any, source_format: string, target_format: string}
    output: {translated: any, confidence: float, metadata: object}
    
  /v1/knowledge/query:
    method: GraphQL
    schema: Dynamic based on connected systems
    caching: Multi-level (L1: Redis, L2: Disk, L3: Computational)
    
  /v1/narrative/generate:
    method: POST
    input: {data_points: array, audience: string, format: string}
    output: {narrative: string, citations: array, confidence: float}
```

Data Schema: Nexus Knowledge Graph

```graphql
type Entity {
  id: ID!
  type: EntityType!
  properties: JSON!
  relationships: [Relationship!]!
  confidence: Float!
  lastUpdated: DateTime!
}

type Relationship {
  source: Entity!
  target: Entity!
  type: RelationshipType!
  weight: Float!
  temporalContext: TemporalContext
}

enum EntityType {
  SYSTEM
  DATA_STREAM
  USER
  PROCESS
  POLICY
  EVENT
}

type TemporalContext {
  validFrom: DateTime!
  validTo: DateTime
  createdAt: DateTime!
}
```

3.3 Performance Specifications

· Translation Throughput: 100K documents/second
· Query Latency: <100ms for 90% of knowledge graph queries
· Narrative Generation: <2 seconds for executive summaries
· Scalability: Horizontal partitioning across semantic domains

---

4. PILLAR 3: SERAPH-RESTOR TECHNICAL SPECIFICATION

4.1 Core Components

4.1.1 Predictive Anomaly Diagnosis Engine

```
Architecture:
├── Multi-Modal Monitoring: Metrics, logs, traces, user feedback
├── Causal Inference Engine: Bayesian networks + do-calculus
├── Root Cause Analyzer: Top-k probable causes with confidence
└── Impact Assessment: Business impact scoring (revenue, users, SLA)

Algorithms:
- Time-series forecasting: Prophet + NeuralProphet hybrids
- Anomaly detection: SR-CNN (Spectral Residual CNN)
- Causal discovery: PC algorithm with temporal extensions
```

4.1.2 Autonomous Healing Controller

· Action Library: 500+ predefined healing actions across stack layers
· Decision Engine: Partially Observable Markov Decision Process (POMDP)
· Safe Exploration: Constrained RL with human-in-the-loop escalation
· Verification: Post-action validation with rollback capability

4.1.3 Resource Flow Optimizer

· Models: Multi-objective optimization (cost, performance, carbon)
· Constraints: SLAs, budgets, regulatory requirements
· Reallocation Speed: Sub-second resource movement
· Prediction Horizon: 48-hour lookahead with 90%+ accuracy

4.2 Key Interfaces

API Gateway: Restor-API v1

```yaml
endpoints:
  /v1/health/diagnose:
    method: POST
    input: {system_id: string, symptoms: array, timeframe: object}
    output: {diagnosis: array, confidence: float, recommended_actions: array}
    
  /v1/heal/execute:
    method: PUT
    input: {action_id: string, parameters: object, dry_run: bool}
    output: {execution_id: string, status: string, estimated_time: int}
    
  /v1/optimize/recommend:
    method: WebSocket (continuous stream)
    output: Real-time optimization suggestions with business impact
```

Data Schema: Restor Health Model

```json
{
  "system_health": {
    "component_id": "string",
    "timestamp": "ISO8601",
    "vital_signs": {
      "performance": {"value": 0.95, "threshold": 0.90},
      "reliability": {"value": 0.999, "threshold": 0.995},
      "efficiency": {"value": 0.85, "threshold": 0.80},
      "security": {"value": 1.0, "threshold": 0.95}
    },
    "anomalies": [
      {
        "type": "performance_degradation",
        "severity": "high",
        "root_causes": ["database_contention", "memory_leak"],
        "confidence": 0.87,
        "recommended_actions": ["scale_database", "restart_service"]
      }
    ],
    "projected_trajectory": {
      "time_horizon": [1, 6, 24], // hours
      "health_score": [0.85, 0.70, 0.40] // without intervention
    }
  }
}
```

4.3 Performance Specifications

· Diagnosis Time: <5 seconds for 95% of incidents
· Healing Action Execution: <30 seconds for automated Tier 1 fixes
· Optimization Cycle: Continuous with 5-minute reassessment intervals
· False Positive Rate: <5% for automated interventions

---

5. CROSS-PILLAR COORDINATION: SERAPH-ORCHESTRATOR

5.1 Meta-Controller Architecture

```
Components:
├── Situation Assessor: Real-time multi-pillar state evaluation
├── Priority Resolver: Dynamic weighting of integrity vs. performance vs. healing
├── Action Sequencer: Ensures non-conflicting cross-pillar actions
└── Learning Feedback Loop: Improves coordination over time

Coordination Patterns:
1. Sentinel detects threat → Nexus provides context → Restor prepares isolation
2. Restor identifies degradation → Sentinel validates safety → Nexus updates dependencies
3. Nexus observes data quality issue → Restor diagnoses cause → Sentinel audits fix
```

5.2 Consensus Protocol

· Algorithm: Federated learning across pillars with gradient sharing
· Decision Making: Weighted voting based on pillar confidence scores
· Conflict Resolution: Temporal priority + business impact scoring
· Fallback: Human escalation for high-impact, low-confidence scenarios

---

6. DATA FABRIC & STORAGE ARCHITECTURE

6.1 Unified Data Layer

```
Storage Tiers:
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ TIER 1: Hot Cache (Redis Cluster)           │
│   - Retention: 24 hours                     │
│   - Access: <1ms                            │
│   - Use: Real-time processing               │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ TIER 2: Operational Store (Cassandra/Scylla)│
│   - Retention: 30 days                      │
│   - Access: <10ms                           │
│   - Use: Recent analysis, dashboards        │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ TIER 3: Analytical Store (ClickHouse)       │
│   - Retention: 13 months                    │
│   - Access: <1s                             │
│   - Use: Trend analysis, ML training        │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ TIER 4: Archive (S3 + Glacier)              │
│   - Retention: 7 years (compliance)         │
│   - Access: Minutes to hours                │
│   - Use: Audit, forensics, long-term trends │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

6.2 Event Streaming Backbone

· Technology: Apache Kafka with Kafka Streams
· Throughput: 10M events/second per cluster
· Retention: Configurable per stream (default: 7 days)
· Partitioning: Semantic partitioning (by domain, tenant, entity type)

6.3 Immutable Audit Ledger

· Technology: Apache Cassandra with custom compaction
· Cryptography: Merkle trees for incremental verification
· Integrity: Every record signed by producing pillar
· Query: Time-window + content-based indexing

---

7. SECURITY & COMPLIANCE SPECIFICATIONS

7.1 Cryptographic Foundation

```
Encryption:
- At-rest: AES-256-GCM
- In-transit: TLS 1.3 with PFS
- Key Management: HashiCorp Vault with HSM integration

Identity & Access:
- Authentication: OAuth 2.1 + OIDC
- Authorization: ABAC (Attribute-Based Access Control)
- Zero-Trust: Every request validated, no implicit trust

Audit & Non-Repudiation:
- Every action cryptographically signed
- Immutable audit trail with tamper evidence
- Regular third-party attestation
```

7.2 Compliance Mappings

· GDPR: Automated data subject request handling
· HIPAA: BAA-ready with PHI detection and encryption
· SOC 2: Continuous control monitoring and evidence collection
· ISO 27001: Control objective mapping and automated testing

